  "prompt": "Any stats/sources on mobile data usage during Football season?",
  "response": "There is considerable data indicating that mobile data usage tends to spike during football season, particularly during key games, playoffs, and events like the Super Bowl. The following are some key statistics and sources that highlight this trend:\n\n1. **Verizon Data Reports:**\n   - Verizon often releases data reports illustrating how mobile data usage increases during football games. For instance, during the 2020 Super Bowl, Verizon reported an 83% increase in mobile data usage at the stadium compared to the previous year's Super Bowl.\n   - Verizon also noted significant spikes in data usage at NFL stadiums during regular season games when compared to non-game days.\n\n2. **AT&T Network Data:**\n   - AT&T has reported similar trends, showing increased mobile data consumption at football stadiums during games. The carrier noted a 48% rise in data usage at the 2021 College Football Playoff National Championship compared to the previous championship game.\n\n3. **Cisco Annual Internet Report:**\n   - Cisco\u2019s Annual Internet Report highlights overall trends in mobile and internet usage. It often mentions notable spikes in data consumption during major sporting events, with football season being a prime example.\n\n4. **App Usage Statistics:**\n   - Apps related to fantasy football, live streaming, sports betting, and social media interactions also see a boost during football season. Data from apps like NFL Mobile, ESPN, DraftKings, and FanDuel show increased engagement and data usage during key football events.\n\n5. **Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) Analysis:**\n   - MNOs like T-Mobile and Sprint have published findings demonstrating similar behaviors among their customers during football season, emphasizing the demand for high-speed data during games for streaming, checking scores, and social media posting.\n\n6. **Streaming Services:**\n   - Streaming services that broadcast football games see substantial increases in traffic and data use. Companies like YouTube TV, Hulu Live, and Amazon Prime Video (for Thursday Night Football) note higher engagement during the season.\n\nUnderstanding these trends is crucial for mobile network operators, app developers, and advertisers to optimize their services and infrastructure during peak times.",
